{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PaRGvZBu46bXWyCCSFK2Pt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough information to compile the findings. Let me write a comprehensive audit report.\n\nKey findings:\n1. **Cluster Health**: 3-node cluster, all nodes running, no alarms, no network partitions\n2. **Version**: RabbitMQ 3.12.14, Erlang 25 - Release series **out of support**\n3. **TLS**: No TLS listeners configured (ssl_listeners: []), only plain AMQP on 5672 and HTTP management on 15672 - **security concern**\n4. **Users**:\n   - `admin` - administrator tag\n   - `app-user` - regular user with no special privileges\n   - `guest` user has been deleted, though the loopback restriction was disabled before removal\n5. **Virtual Hosts**: `/` (default) and `/app`\n6. **Permissions**:\n   - `/` vhost: only `admin` has permissions (.*,.*,.*)\n   - `/app` vhost: both `admin` and `app-user` have full permissions (.*,.*,.*)\n7. **Policies**: No policies defined on either vhost - **no HA/mirroring policies, no TTL, no DLX configured**\n8. **Queues**: `app-queue` exists on `/app` as a classic, durable queue with no special arguments; the default vhost has no queues\n9. **Queue Type**: Classic queues are in use, though quorum queues are available but not deployed - a potential reliability gap\n10. **Configuration**: The guest user setting is disabled, and the removed guest user wouldn't have had loopback restrictions anyway\n11. **Plugins**: Management and Kubernetes peer discovery plugins are active\n12. **Secrets**: Three secrets are configured for admin, app user, and the Erlang cookie\n\nNow I'm preparing to document these findings and create the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":829,"cache_read_input_tokens":35637,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_to