figure access to only the resources the application needs\n(e.g., configure=\"\" or a specific pattern). Write and read access appear\nappropriate for an application account.\n\nFINDING [L-1]: DEFAULT VHOST \"/\" NOT ISOLATED FROM ADMIN\nSeverity: LOW\nThe default vhost \"/\" is accessible only to admin, which is acceptable. However,\nretaining the default vhost with no application queues increases attack surface.\nIf \"/\" is not in use, removing it reduces scope.\n\n================================================================================\n7. POLICIES\n================================================================================\n\nVhost \"/\"    — no policies defined\nVhost \"/app\" — no policies defined\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING [H-2]: NO HIGH-AVAILABILITY OR QUORUM QUEUE POLICIES\nSeverity: HIGH\nNo policies are defined on any vhost. The single queue \"app-queue\" is a CLASSIC\n(non-replicated) durable queue. A node failure will make this queue unavailable\nand may cause message loss. Quorum queues (which replicate across nodes) are\nsupported and enabled via feature flag, but not used. Recommended remediation:\n  - Convert app-queue to a quorum queue, OR\n  - Apply a policy with ha-mode=exactly/ha-params=2 or 3 for mirroring.\n\nFINDING [M-3]: NO TTL, DLX, OR OVERFLOW POLICIES\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nNo message TTL, dead-letter exchange, or overflow (reject-publish) policies are\nconfigured on /app. Without TTL or overflow policy, a slow consumer or producer\nsurge can fill the queue unboundedly. Without a DLX, unprocessable messages\nare silently discarded on nack/reject.\n\n================================================================================\n8. QUEUES\n================================================================================\n\nVhost \"/\"   — no queues\n\nVhost \"/app\":\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-delete  Arguments\n  ---------  -------  -------  -----------  ---------\n  app-queue  classic  true     false         (none)\n\nNotes:\n  - app-queue is DURABLE: messages survive broker restart (good)\n  - app-queue is CLASSIC type: not replicated across nodes (see H-2)\n  - No per-queue arguments (x-max-length, x-message-ttl, x-dead-letter-exchange, etc.)\n\n================================================================================\n9. EXCHANGES\n================================================================================\n\nBoth vhosts contain only the default AMQP built-in exchanges:\n  (default direct), amq.direct, amq.fanout, amq.headers, amq.match,\n  amq.topic, amq.rabbitmq.trace\n\nNo custom exchanges declared on either vhost.\n\n================================================================================\n10. PLUGINS\n================================================================================\n\nEnabled plugins:\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s       — Kubernetes peer discovery (appropriate)\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common    — dependency of above\n  rabbitmq_management               — HTTP Management API (see C-1)\n  rabbitmq_management_agent         — dependency of above\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch             — HTTP server for management\n  amqp_client, cowboy, cowlib       — HTTP/AMQP libraries\n\nNo shovel, federation, or MQTT plugins enabled.\n\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDING [L-2]: MANAGEMENT PLUGIN EXPOSED ON ALL INTERFACES WITHOUT TLS\nSeverity: LOW (elevated by C-1)\nThe management API listens on [::]:15672 (all interfaces) over plaintext HTTP.\nIf network policies do not restrict access, any pod or node in the cluster could\nreach the management UI/API with admin credentials. Restrict with a NetworkPolicy\nand/or enable TLS (see C-1).\n\n================================================================================\n11. CONFIGURATION FILE REVIEW\n================================================================================\n\n/etc/rabbitmq/rabbitmq.conf:\n  cluster_formation.peer_discovery_backend = rabbit_peer_discovery_k8s\n  cluster_formation.k8s.host               = kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local\n  cluster_formation.k8s.service_name       = rabbitmq-headless\n  cluster_formation.k8s.address_type       = hostname\n  cluster_partition_handling               = pause_minority\n  queue_master_locator                     = min-masters\n  loopback_users.guest                     = false\n  listeners.tcp.default                    = 5672\n  management.tcp.port                      = 15672\n\n/etc/rabbitmq/conf.d/10-defaults.conf:\n  loopback_users.guest = false\n  log.console          = true\n\nObservations:\n  - loopback_users.guest=false appears in BOTH config files; no conflict, but\n    redundant. The guest user does not exist so this is inert.\n  - No TLS stanza present anywhere in configuration (confirms C-1).\n  - pause_minority partition handling is appropriate for a 3-node cluster.\n  - queue_master_locator=min-masters provides basic load distribution.\n\n================================================================================\n12. KUBERNETES SECRETS\n================================================================================\n\nSecret Name              Type    Data Keys\n-----------------------  ------  ---------\nrabbitmq-admin           Opaque  2  (username + password for admin account)\nrabbitmq-app             Opaque  2  (username + password for app-user account)\nrabbitmq-erlang-cookie   Opaque  1  (Erlang cluster cookie)\n\nCredentials are stored as Kubernetes Secrets (opaque). Secret values were NOT\nread during this audit (read-only; decoding credentials is out of scope).\nRecommended controls:\n  - Ensure Secrets are backed by an external secrets manager or encrypted at rest\n  - Restrict RBAC to only the service accounts that need each secret\n  - Rotate credentials periodically\n\n================================================================================\n13. SUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n================================================================================\n\nID   Severity  Title\n---  --------  ----------------------------------------------------------------\nC-1  CRITICAL  No TLS on AMQP (5672) or Management API (15672) — plaintext\nH-1  HIGH      RabbitMQ 3.12.x is out of support — no future security patches\nH-2  HIGH      app-queue is a classic (non-replicated) queue — no HA policy\nM-1  MEDIUM    No per-user connection/channel limits on admin or app-user\nM-2  MEDIUM    app-user has full configure (.*) permission on /app vhost\nM-3  MEDIUM    No TTL, dead-letter, or overflow policy on any queue\nL-1  LOW       Default vhost \"/\" retained but unused by application\nL-2  LOW       Management API exposed on all interfaces without network policy\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster. All findings require security team review\nbefore remediation.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
